<br>
<!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>However</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END-->, such analysis is still telling in the long term.<br>
<br>
Consider the following simplified, but common situation:<br>
<br>
Raid against <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Boffo The Clown Lord</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.<br>
Strategy: <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Main Tank</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> holds aggro, is chain healed.  Damage dealers deal damage.<br>
<br>
In this scenario, suppose that all support roles are adequately covered, and there is one more raid slot available.  The raid leader is faced with a choice between an additional melee, let's say a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Rogue</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, and an additional <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Magician</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  Who do you pick?<br>
<br>
Yes, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> DPS</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> analysis ignores the utility of being a caster and the support costs of melee.  Yes, casters in general undervalue their non-damage utility.  All the things you said are wonderful, and are among the reasons I play a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Magician</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.<br>
<br>
But the fact remains that at the margin, an additional <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> melee</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> brings more utility to the most common raid situation than does an additional <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Magician</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  In so far as this excludes <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Magicians</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> from play, it is a legitimate class balance concern.  And <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> DPS</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> analysis most clearly reveals this imbalance.<br>
<br>
This is why we really do need to ask the question: <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> &quot;What is Class Balance?&quot;</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Razamatazz Pizzazz</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Abuser of EZC</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--></i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/uzacatac.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Zacatac</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Arch Mage</span><br>  Posts: 414<br> <font color=#333333>(1/16/02 9:37:06 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm32.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=46.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_exclamation_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Random thoughts on class balancing</span><hr size=1> Well pick a mob that is mage nuke-able.<br>
<br>
Then have a raid group of--<br>
Mage, Bard, Necro, Enchanter, Rogue, Shaman <br>
<br>
Rogue can have all the buffs he wants.  So can Mage and his pet.<br>
<br>
During the battle, necro is mana-dumping mage, shaman is healing necro, bard is playing manasong, etc. so that the mage has C2+bardsong+necro mana+any FT items+epic pet.<br>
<br>
The rogue fully buffed up by other support classes, and the mage is fully buffed up by support classes.<br>
<br>
NOW, if the rogue stills can outdamage us, then we are definately in trouble.<br>
