<br>
However, there are many hidden assumptions here.  For instance, it ignores the <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>supposed</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> (and not yet clearly demonstrated or measured)</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> value of <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>burn down.</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END-->.  That is, it is assumed by many, including <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Verant</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, that melee <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>ought</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> to be the greatest and most reliable source of long time damage.  In return, casters are imagined to be able to do a vast amount of damage in a short amount of time.  In that case, the additional control over the melee of being able to kill a specific foe quickly before something horrible goes wrong is supposed to compensate for the loss in long term damage.<br>
<br>
If this is true, one would expect the rogue to outdamage us over time.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Raz</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
